  %section
    %h3 Transport Layer Security
    %p (AKA Secure Sockets Layer)
  %section
    %h3 What is it?
    %ul
      %li Protocol used for secure electronic communications
      %li Designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering
      %li Used in many applications such as web browsing, email and text-messaging
      %li Practical form of public key cryptography
      %li Also referred to as "Secure Sockets Layer" or "SSL"
  %section
    %h3 Why Do We Need it?
    %ul
      %li Very important information is stored electronically
      %li Much of this information is accessible from the web
      %li Without the proper protections, this information can be gathered by bad people to use for nefarious acts
  %section
    %h3 How Does it Work?
    %ul
      %li The communication between two devices is encrypted using a shared secret
      %li The shared secret is only known to the devices communicating
      %li Each message received is decrypted using a code known only to the receiver
  %section
    %h3 Best Practices
    %ul
      %li Do not browse websites which don't have valid SSL certificates
      %li Use more technology which was developed with security in mind
      %li Do not use any versions of the SSL protocol, use TLS instead (preferably TLSv1.2)
  %section
